TY  - JOUR
T1  - The End of the American Dream? Inequality and Segregation in US                         Cities
AU  - Fogli, Alessandra
AU  - Guerrieri, Veronica
AU  - Ponder, Mark
AU  - Prato, Marta
Y1  - 2025/10/28
PY  - 2025
DA  - 2026/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/739328
DO  - 10.1086/739328
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 1110
EP  - 1158
VL  - 134
IS  - 4
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - Since the 1980s, the United States has experienced both an increase in income inequality and a rise in residential segregation by income. We develop a general equilibrium model with residential choice, where segregation and inequality amplify each other because of a local spillover affecting educational returns. We calibrate the model to a representative US metro in 1980 and use the micro estimates of neighborhood exposure effects in Chetty and Hendren (2018b) to discipline the spillover. We then explore the economy?s response to an unexpected skill premium shock and show that segregation played a significant role in amplifying the increase in inequality.
AB  - Since the 1980s, the United States has experienced both an increase in income inequality and a rise in residential segregation by income. We develop a general equilibrium model with residential choice, where segregation and inequality amplify each other because of a local spillover affecting educational returns. We calibrate the model to a representative US metro in 1980 and use the micro estimates of neighborhood exposure effects in Chetty and Hendren (2018b) to discipline the spillover. We then explore the economy?s response to an unexpected skill premium shock and show that segregation played a significant role in amplifying the increase in inequality.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/739328
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/739328
Y2  - 2026/04/24
