TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Social Integration of International Migrants: Evidence from                         the Networks of Syrians in Germany
AU  - Bailey, Michael
AU  - Johnston, Drew
AU  - Koenen, Martin
AU  - Kuchler, Theresa
AU  - Russel, Dominic
AU  - Stroebel, Johannes
Y1  - 2025/10/28
PY  - 2025
DA  - 2026/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/739335
DO  - 10.1086/739335
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 1159
EP  - 1209
VL  - 134
IS  - 4
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - We use Facebook data to study Syrian migrants? social integration in Germany, establishing five findings: (1) Migrants? social integration varies across regions, driven by causal, place-based effects. (2) This spatial variation reflects how frequently Germans befriend neighbors and how likely they are to befriend migrants versus other Germans. Using a mover?s design, we show that both factors are shaped more by local institutions and policies than by persistent native characteristics. (3) Integration courses boost intergroup friending rates. (4) Migrants receive help from Germans, such as finding jobs or housing. (5) Germans quasi-randomly exposed to migrants in high school are likelier to befriend migrants later.
AB  - We use Facebook data to study Syrian migrants? social integration in Germany, establishing five findings: (1) Migrants? social integration varies across regions, driven by causal, place-based effects. (2) This spatial variation reflects how frequently Germans befriend neighbors and how likely they are to befriend migrants versus other Germans. Using a mover?s design, we show that both factors are shaped more by local institutions and policies than by persistent native characteristics. (3) Integration courses boost intergroup friending rates. (4) Migrants receive help from Germans, such as finding jobs or housing. (5) Germans quasi-randomly exposed to migrants in high school are likelier to befriend migrants later.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/739335
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/739335
Y2  - 2026/04/24
